[Language family](/Language_family)  

[Language isolate](/Language_isolate)  
Dialects  

The Timucua language is classified as a **language isolate**, meaning it bears no demonstrable genealogical relationship to any other known language family.  Its closest hypothesized relatives—such as the [Muskogean](/Muskogean_languages) languages of the Southeastern United States, or various [South American families](/South_American_families) including [Cariban](/Cariban_languages), [Arawakan](/Arawakan_languages), [Chibchan languages](/Chibchan_languages), and [Warao](/Warao_language)—remain unproven.  The language’s isolation is underscored by the paucity of lexical borrowing and the uniqueness of its grammatical structures.  

### Dialects  

Father Pareja originally identified **nine or ten dialects**, each tied to a specific tribal grouping within the Timucua cultural sphere.  These dialects exhibit only minor phonological and lexical differences, primarily serving to mark tribal boundaries.  

* [Timucua proper](/Timucua) – [Northern Utina](/Northern_Utina) tribe, between the lower (northern) [St. Johns River](/St._Johns_River) and the [Suwannee River](/Suwannee_River), north of the [Santa Fe River](/Santa_Fe_River_(Florida)) in [Florida](/Florida) and into southern [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)) in [Georgia_(U.S._state)].  
* [Potano](/Potano) – [Potano](/Potano) and possibly the [Yustaga](/Yustaga) and [Ocale](/Ocale) tribes, between the [Aucilla River](/Aucilla_River) and the Suwannee River in [Florida](/Florida) and extending into southern [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), but not along the coast of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) (with the possible exception of the mouth of the Suwannee River), between the Suwannee River and the [Oklawaha River](/Oklawaha_River) south of the [Santa Fe River](/Santa_Fe_River_(Florida)), extending south into the area between the [Oklawaha River](/Oklawaha_River) and the [Withlacoochee](/Withlacoochee_River_(Florida)) rivers.  
* [Itafi (or Icafui )](/Itafi) – [Icafui](/Icafui)/[Cascange] and [Ibi](/Ibi_people) tribes, in [southeast Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)], along the coast north of [Cumberland Island](/Cumberland_Island) north to the [Altamaha River](/Altamaha_River) and inland west of the [Yufera tribe](/Yufera_people).  
* [Yufera](/Yufera) – [Yufera tribe](/Yufera_people), in [southeast Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)], on the mainland west of [Cumberland Island](/Cumberland_Island).  
* [Mocama](/Mocama) (Timucua for 'ocean') (called [Agua Salada](/Agua_Salada) in [Hann](/Hann) 1996 and elsewhere) – [Mocama](/Mocama), including the [Tacatacuru](/Tacatacuru) (on [Cumberland Island](/Cumberland_Island) in [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state))) and the [Saturiwa](/Saturiwa) (in what is now [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville)) tribes, along the [Atlantic](/Atlantic_Ocean) coast of [Florida](/Florida) from the [St. Marys River](/St._Marys_River_(Florida/Georgia)) to below the mouth of the [St. Johns River](/St._Johns_River), including the lowest part of the [St. Johns River].  
* [Agua Salada](/Agua_Salada) (Spanish for 'salt water' ( Maritime in [Hann](/Hann) 1996) – tribal affiliation unclear, the [Atlantic coast](/Atlantic_coast) in the vicinity of [St. Augustine](/St._Augustine,_Florida) and inland to the adjacent stretch of the [St. Johns River].  
* [Tucururu](/Tucururu) – uncertain, possibly in [south-central Florida](/Central_Florida) (a village called [Tucuru](/Tucuru) was "forty [leagues](/League_(unit)) from [St. Augustine](/St._Augustine,_Florida)").

All of the linguistic documentation is from the [Mocama](/Mocama) and [Potano](/Potano) dialects.  Scholars do not agree on the exact number of distinct dialects; some argue that Pareja’s [Agua Salada] should be treated as a separate dialect, while others view it as an alternate name for [Mocama].  

### Writing system  

